INSERT INTO threads VALUES('019dcb0d-6155-7872-a8ae-2da895013196','C:\Users\Li\.codex\sessions\2026\04\27\rollout-2026-04-27T02-29-05-019dcb0d-6155-7872-a8ae-2da895013196.jsonl',1777228145,1779967762,'mcp','custom','C:\Users\Li\Desktop\EEGNRNet论文文件',replace('I''m going to present a complete ML research project for your critical review. Please act as a senior ML reviewer (NeurIPS/ICML level) and provide a thorough, brutally honest assessment.\n\n# Paper Title\nEEGNRNet: A Deep Learning Framework for Sleep Staging Based on Graph Neural Networks with Non-Stationary Signals\n\n# Target Venue\nNeurocomputing (SCI Q2, IF=6.5, ~80% acceptance rate, 5.7-month review cycle)\n\n# Research Problem\nSleep staging from single-channel EEG signals is a critical but challenging task in sleep medicine. Existing methods face two major limitations:\n1. Most treat EEG channels independently, ignoring spatial dependencies\n2. Most assume stationarity, but EEG signals are inherently non-stationary\n\n# Proposed Method: EEGNRNet\n\n## Core Architecture\nEEGNRNet integrates three key components:\n\n1. **Graph Structure Learning Module (GSLM)**:\n   - Learns spatial relationships between different EEG frequency bands\n   - Constructs adjacency matrix from multi-scale frequency components\n   - Formula: A^l = softmax(LeakyReLU(W_a · concat(v_i^l, v_j^l)))\n   - Where v_i^l = LayerNorm(σ(W_v · f_i^l + b_v))\n\n2. **Non-Stationary Signal Processing Module (NSPM)**:\n   - Addresses non-stationarity through two mechanisms:\n   - a) Adaptive normalization across different frequency bands\n   - b) Signal-dependent weight modulation\n   - Adaptive normalization: \hat{x}_k = (x_k - μ_k) / (σ_k + ε)\n   - Weight modulation: w_k = σ(W_w · x_k + b_w) ⊙ γ_k\n   - Handles distribution shifts across sleep stages\n\n3. **Multi-Scale Temporal Representation Module (MSTRM)**:\n   - Parallel dilated convolutions (dilation factors: 1, 2, 4, 8)\n   - Each branch extracts features at different temporal scales\n   - Formula: F_d = Conv1D(x, kernel=3, dilation=d)\n   - Captures sleep stage transitions and micro-architectures\n\n## Network Architecture\n- Input: 30-second EEG epochs\n- Preprocessing: Multi-band decomposition using DBWT (delta, theta, alpha, beta, gamma)\n- Feature extraction: Multi-scale temporal convolutions\n- Graph convolutions: 2 layers, hidden dim=128\n- Classification: Fully connected + Softmax (5 classes: W, N1, N2, N3, REM)\n\n# Datasets\n\n## Sleep-EDF\n- 20 healthy subjects, 8-14 hours each\n- Fpz-Cz channel, 100 Hz sampling\n- 5 classes: W, N1, N2, N3, REM\n- Train/validation/test: 14/3/3 subjects\n\n## MASS-SS3\n- 62 healthy subjects, full-night recordings\n- F3-A2 channel, 256 Hz sampling\n- Same 5-class classification\n- Train/validation/test: 44/9/9 subjects\n\n# Baselines Compared\n1. **SleepEEGNet**: CNN-based sleep staging\n2. **U-Time**: Encoder-decoder architecture\n3. **AttnSleep**: Attention-based CNN-RNN\n4. **TS-CAN**: Transformer-based\n5. **SleepTransformer**: Transformer architecture\n\n# Evaluation Metrics\n- Accuracy (ACC)\n- Macro F1-score (MF1)\n- Cohen''s Kappa (κ)\n- Per-class precision, recall, F1\n\n# Key Results\n\n## Sleep-EDF Dataset\n| Method | ACC | MF1 | κ |\n|--------|-----|-----|---|\n| SleepEEGNet | 78.3% | 70.2% | 0.72 |\n| U-Time | 79.1% | 71.8% | 0.73 |\n| AttnSleep | 80.2% | 73.5% | 0.75 |\n| TS-CAN | 81.5% | 75.3% | 0.77 |\n| SleepTransformer | 82.1% | 76.8% | 0.78 |\n| **EEGNRNet** | **84.7%** | **79.3%** | **0.81** |\n\n## MASS-SS3 Dataset\n| Method | ACC | MF1 | κ |\n|--------|-----|-----|---|\n| SleepEEGNet | 82.1% | 74.5% | 0.76 |\n| U-Time | 83.2% | 76.1% | 0.78 |\n| AttnSleep | 84.3% | 78.2% | 0.80 |\n| TS-CAN | 85.6% | 80.3% | 0.82 |\n| SleepTransformer | 86.4% | 81.7% | 0.83 |\n| **EEGNRNet** | **88.9%** | **84.2%** | **0.86** |\n\n# Ablation Studies\n\n## Component Analysis on Sleep-EDF\n| Model | ACC | MF1 | κ |\n|-------|-----|-----|---|\n| Base (no GSLM, no NSPM) | 79.8% | 72.1% | 0.74 |\n| +GSLM | 81.5% | 75.3% | 0.77 |\n| +NSPM | 82.7% | 77.1% | 0.78 |\n| +MSTRM | 83.9% | 78.5% | 0.80 |\n| Full EEGNRNet | 84.7% | 79.3% | 0.81 |\n\n## Graph Structure Analysis\n- Compared: random graph, fully connected, learned graph\n- Learned graph achieved 3.2% improvement over random\n\n## Temporal Scale Analysis\n- Compared: single-scale (dilation=1), multi-scale (1,2,4,8)\n- Multi-scale achieved 2.4% improvement\n\n# Statistical Significance\n- Paired t-tests: p < 0.01 for all comparisons vs. best baseline\n- Bootstrap confidence intervals: 95% CI reported for all metrics\n\n# Computational Analysis\n- Parameters: 1.2M\n- FLOPs: 0.8G\n- Inference time: 3.2 ms/epoch\n- Training time: 4.2 hours (Sleep-EDF)\n\n# Limitations Acknowledged in Paper\n1. Only tested on healthy subjects - need clinical validation\n2. Single-channel EEG - multi-channel could improve\n3. Computational cost higher than simpler models\n4. Limited interpretability of learned graph structure\n\n# Specific Questions for Reviewer\n\n1. **Sufficient Contribution?** Does the 2.6-3.3% improvement over SleepTransformer (the strongest baseline) justify the methodological complexity for a Q2 venue? For a top venue (Q1), would you consider this sufficient?\n\n2. **Ablation Study Depth:** Are there additional ablation studies you''d want to see? For example:\n   - What if we remove adaptive normalization from NSPM?\n   - What if we use different graph construction methods?\n   - Sensitivity to different band decomposition methods?\n\n3. **Missing Experiments:** What critical experiments are missing that would strengthen the story? Consider:\n   - Cross-dataset generalization (train on Sleep-EDF, test on MASS, etc.)\n   - Robustness to noise/artifacts\n   - Subject-specific vs. subject-independent performance\n   - Clinical relevance on patient data (not just healthy subjects)\n\n4. **Narrative Strength:** Is the story coherent? The paper argues: (a) EEG has spatial structure → graph learning, (b) EEG is non-stationary → adaptive processing, (c) Sleep stages have multi-scale patterns → temporal modeling. Does this logic hold?\n\n5. **Technical Concerns:** \n   - Is the graph construction method justified for single-channel EEG? (The paper argues frequency bands have spatial relationships, but this is debatable)\n   - Is the non-stationarity handling actually addressing distribution shift, or is it just normalization?\n   - Are the baseline implementations fair and optimized?\n\n6. **Comparison Landscape:** Are we missing important baselines? What about:\n   - Other GNN-based sleep staging methods\n   - Recent diffusion-based approaches\n   - Self-supervised pretraining methods\n\n7. **For Neurocomputing:** Given this is a Q2 venue with 80% acceptance, is the paper likely to be accepted? What are the main strengths and weaknesses for this specific venue?\n\nPlease provide:\n1. Overall assessment (accept/reject/revise for both Q2 and Q1 venues)\n2. Top 3-5 most critical weaknesses to address\n3. Specific missing experiments with their expected impact\n4. Narrative/structural improvements needed\n5. Any technical concerns about the method itself\n\nBe brutally honest - what would kill this paper at a top venue? What are the easiest wins to improve acceptance chances?','\n',char(10)),'{"type":"managed","file_system":{"type":"restricted","entries":[{"path":{"type":"special","value":{"kind":"root"}},"access":"read"}]},"network":"restricted"}','on-request',68883,1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'0.125.0',replace('I''m going to present a complete ML research project for your critical review. Please act as a senior ML reviewer (NeurIPS/ICML level) and provide a thorough, brutally honest assessment.\n\n# Paper Title\nEEGNRNet: A Deep Learning Framework for Sleep Staging Based on Graph Neural Networks with Non-Stationary Signals\n\n# Target Venue\nNeurocomputing (SCI Q2, IF=6.5, ~80% acceptance rate, 5.7-month review cycle)\n\n# Research Problem\nSleep staging from single-channel EEG signals is a critical but challenging task in sleep medicine. Existing methods face two major limitations:\n1. Most treat EEG channels independently, ignoring spatial dependencies\n2. Most assume stationarity, but EEG signals are inherently non-stationary\n\n# Proposed Method: EEGNRNet\n\n## Core Architecture\nEEGNRNet integrates three key components:\n\n1. **Graph Structure Learning Module (GSLM)**:\n   - Learns spatial relationships between different EEG frequency bands\n   - Constructs adjacency matrix from multi-scale frequency components\n   - Formula: A^l = softmax(LeakyReLU(W_a · concat(v_i^l, v_j^l)))\n   - Where v_i^l = LayerNorm(σ(W_v · f_i^l + b_v))\n\n2. **Non-Stationary Signal Processing Module (NSPM)**:\n   - Addresses non-stationarity through two mechanisms:\n   - a) Adaptive normalization across different frequency bands\n   - b) Signal-dependent weight modulation\n   - Adaptive normalization: \hat{x}_k = (x_k - μ_k) / (σ_k + ε)\n   - Weight modulation: w_k = σ(W_w · x_k + b_w) ⊙ γ_k\n   - Handles distribution shifts across sleep stages\n\n3. **Multi-Scale Temporal Representation Module (MSTRM)**:\n   - Parallel dilated convolutions (dilation factors: 1, 2, 4, 8)\n   - Each branch extracts features at different temporal scales\n   - Formula: F_d = Conv1D(x, kernel=3, dilation=d)\n   - Captures sleep stage transitions and micro-architectures\n\n## Network Architecture\n- Input: 30-second EEG epochs\n- Preprocessing: Multi-band decomposition using DBWT (delta, theta, alpha, beta, gamma)\n- Feature extraction: Multi-scale temporal convolutions\n- Graph convolutions: 2 layers, hidden dim=128\n- Classification: Fully connected + Softmax (5 classes: W, N1, N2, N3, REM)\n\n# Datasets\n\n## Sleep-EDF\n- 20 healthy subjects, 8-14 hours each\n- Fpz-Cz channel, 100 Hz sampling\n- 5 classes: W, N1, N2, N3, REM\n- Train/validation/test: 14/3/3 subjects\n\n## MASS-SS3\n- 62 healthy subjects, full-night recordings\n- F3-A2 channel, 256 Hz sampling\n- Same 5-class classification\n- Train/validation/test: 44/9/9 subjects\n\n# Baselines Compared\n1. **SleepEEGNet**: CNN-based sleep staging\n2. **U-Time**: Encoder-decoder architecture\n3. **AttnSleep**: Attention-based CNN-RNN\n4. **TS-CAN**: Transformer-based\n5. **SleepTransformer**: Transformer architecture\n\n# Evaluation Metrics\n- Accuracy (ACC)\n- Macro F1-score (MF1)\n- Cohen''s Kappa (κ)\n- Per-class precision, recall, F1\n\n# Key Results\n\n## Sleep-EDF Dataset\n| Method | ACC | MF1 | κ |\n|--------|-----|-----|---|\n| SleepEEGNet | 78.3% | 70.2% | 0.72 |\n| U-Time | 79.1% | 71.8% | 0.73 |\n| AttnSleep | 80.2% | 73.5% | 0.75 |\n| TS-CAN | 81.5% | 75.3% | 0.77 |\n| SleepTransformer | 82.1% | 76.8% | 0.78 |\n| **EEGNRNet** | **84.7%** | **79.3%** | **0.81** |\n\n## MASS-SS3 Dataset\n| Method | ACC | MF1 | κ |\n|--------|-----|-----|---|\n| SleepEEGNet | 82.1% | 74.5% | 0.76 |\n| U-Time | 83.2% | 76.1% | 0.78 |\n| AttnSleep | 84.3% | 78.2% | 0.80 |\n| TS-CAN | 85.6% | 80.3% | 0.82 |\n| SleepTransformer | 86.4% | 81.7% | 0.83 |\n| **EEGNRNet** | **88.9%** | **84.2%** | **0.86** |\n\n# Ablation Studies\n\n## Component Analysis on Sleep-EDF\n| Model | ACC | MF1 | κ |\n|-------|-----|-----|---|\n| Base (no GSLM, no NSPM) | 79.8% | 72.1% | 0.74 |\n| +GSLM | 81.5% | 75.3% | 0.77 |\n| +NSPM | 82.7% | 77.1% | 0.78 |\n| +MSTRM | 83.9% | 78.5% | 0.80 |\n| Full EEGNRNet | 84.7% | 79.3% | 0.81 |\n\n## Graph Structure Analysis\n- Compared: random graph, fully connected, learned graph\n- Learned graph achieved 3.2% improvement over random\n\n## Temporal Scale Analysis\n- Compared: single-scale (dilation=1), multi-scale (1,2,4,8)\n- Multi-scale achieved 2.4% improvement\n\n# Statistical Significance\n- Paired t-tests: p < 0.01 for all comparisons vs. best baseline\n- Bootstrap confidence intervals: 95% CI reported for all metrics\n\n# Computational Analysis\n- Parameters: 1.2M\n- FLOPs: 0.8G\n- Inference time: 3.2 ms/epoch\n- Training time: 4.2 hours (Sleep-EDF)\n\n# Limitations Acknowledged in Paper\n1. Only tested on healthy subjects - need clinical validation\n2. Single-channel EEG - multi-channel could improve\n3. Computational cost higher than simpler models\n4. Limited interpretability of learned graph structure\n\n# Specific Questions for Reviewer\n\n1. **Sufficient Contribution?** Does the 2.6-3.3% improvement over SleepTransformer (the strongest baseline) justify the methodological complexity for a Q2 venue? For a top venue (Q1), would you consider this sufficient?\n\n2. **Ablation Study Depth:** Are there additional ablation studies you''d want to see? For example:\n   - What if we remove adaptive normalization from NSPM?\n   - What if we use different graph construction methods?\n   - Sensitivity to different band decomposition methods?\n\n3. **Missing Experiments:** What critical experiments are missing that would strengthen the story? Consider:\n   - Cross-dataset generalization (train on Sleep-EDF, test on MASS, etc.)\n   - Robustness to noise/artifacts\n   - Subject-specific vs. subject-independent performance\n   - Clinical relevance on patient data (not just healthy subjects)\n\n4. **Narrative Strength:** Is the story coherent? The paper argues: (a) EEG has spatial structure → graph learning, (b) EEG is non-stationary → adaptive processing, (c) Sleep stages have multi-scale patterns → temporal modeling. Does this logic hold?\n\n5. **Technical Concerns:** \n   - Is the graph construction method justified for single-channel EEG? (The paper argues frequency bands have spatial relationships, but this is debatable)\n   - Is the non-stationarity handling actually addressing distribution shift, or is it just normalization?\n   - Are the baseline implementations fair and optimized?\n\n6. **Comparison Landscape:** Are we missing important baselines? What about:\n   - Other GNN-based sleep staging methods\n   - Recent diffusion-based approaches\n   - Self-supervised pretraining methods\n\n7. **For Neurocomputing:** Given this is a Q2 venue with 80% acceptance, is the paper likely to be accepted? What are the main strengths and weaknesses for this specific venue?\n\nPlease provide:\n1. Overall assessment (accept/reject/revise for both Q2 and Q1 venues)\n2. Top 3-5 most critical weaknesses to address\n3. Specific missing experiments with their expected impact\n4. Narrative/structural improvements needed\n5. Any technical concerns about the method itself\n\nBe brutally honest - what would kill this paper at a top venue? What are the easiest wins to improve acceptance chances?','\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,'enabled','gpt-5.5','xhigh',NULL,1777228145022,1779967762966,NULL,replace('I''m going to present a complete ML research project for your critical review. Please act as a senior ML reviewer (NeurIPS/ICML level) and provide a thorough, brutally honest assessment.\n\n# Paper Title\nEEGNRNet: A Deep Learning Framework for Sleep Staging Based on Graph Neural Networks with Non-Stationary Signals\n\n# Target Venue\nNeurocomputing (SCI Q2, IF=6.5, ~80% acceptance rate, 5.7-month review cycle)\n\n# Research Problem\nSleep staging from single-channel EEG signals is a critical but challenging task in sleep medicine. Existing methods face two major limitations:\n1. Most treat EEG channels independently, ignoring spatial dependencies\n2. Most assume stationarity, but EEG signals are inherently non-stationary\n\n# Proposed Method: EEGNRNet\n\n## Core Architecture\nEEGNRNet integrates three key components:\n\n1. **Graph Structure Learning Module (GSLM)**:\n   - Learns spatial relationships between different EEG frequency bands\n   - Constructs adjacency matrix from multi-scale frequency components\n   - Formula: A^l = softmax(LeakyReLU(W_a · concat(v_i^l, v_j^l)))\n   - Where v_i^l = LayerNorm(σ(W_v · f_i^l + b_v))\n\n2. **Non-Stationary Signal Processing Module (NSPM)**:\n   - Addresses non-stationarity through two mechanisms:\n   - a) Adaptive normalization across different frequency bands\n   - b) Signal-dependent weight modula