n   - Cross-dataset generalization (train on Sleep-EDF, test on MASS, etc.)\n   - Robustness to noise/artifacts\n   - Subject-specific vs. subject-independent performance\n   - Clinical relevance on patient data (not just healthy subjects)\n\n4. **Narrative Strength:** Is the story coherent? The paper argues: (a) EEG has spatial structure → graph learning, (b) EEG is non-stationary → adaptive processing, (c) Sleep stages have multi-scale patterns → temporal modeling. Does this logic hold?\n\n5. **Technical Concerns:** \n   - Is the graph construction method justified for single-channel EEG? (The paper argues frequency bands have spatial relationships, but this is debatable)\n   - Is the non-stationarity handling actually addressing distribution shift, or is it just normalization?\n   - Are the baseline implementations fair and optimized?\n\n6. **Comparison Landscape:** Are we missing important baselines? What about:\n   - Other GNN-based sleep staging methods\n   - Recent diffusion-based approaches\n   - Self-supervised pretraining methods\n\n7. **For Neurocomputing:** Given this is a Q2 venue with 80% acceptance, is the paper likely to be accepted? What are the main strengths and weaknesses for this specific venue?\n\nPlease provide:\n1. Overall assessment (accept/reject/revise for both Q2 and Q1 venues)\n2. Top 3-5 most critical weaknesses to address\n3. Specific missing experiments with their expected impact\n4. Narrative/structural improvements needed\n5. Any technical concerns about the method itself\n\nBe brutally honest - what would kill this paper at a top venue? What are the easiest wins to improve acceptance chances?','\n',char(10)),1779967762,1779967762966,'legacy');
INSERT INTO threads VALUES('019dcd02-f6f3-71c3-9eaa-a3416dae914e','C:\Users\Li\.codex\sessions\2026\04\27\rollout-2026-04-27T11-36-56-019dcd02-f6f3-71c3-9eaa-a3416dae914e.jsonl',1777261016,1779967762,'mcp','custom','C:\Users\Li\Desktop\EEGNRNet论文文件\Neurocomputing投稿文件',replace('I''m going to present a complete ML research paper for your critical review. Please act as a senior ML reviewer (NeurIPS/ICML level) and provide a comprehensive assessment.\n\n## Paper Title\nEEGNRNet: A Neuro Rhythm-aware Network for Motor Imagery Brain–Computer Interface\n\n## Venue\nSubmitted to Neurocomputing (journal)\n\n## Authors\nZhiqiang Li, Guoqiang Hu, Wei Zhao, Junning Deng, Xinqiang Xie\n\n## Problem Statement\nMotor imagery electroencephalogram (MI EEG) decoding is a core challenge in BCI systems. The rhythmic structure of EEG signals exhibits:\n- Multi-frequency coexistence\n- Dynamic temporal variations  \n- Significant inter-subject variability\n\nThese properties challenge conventional decoding methods in terms of robustness and generalizability.\n\n## Proposed Solution: EEGNRNet\nA novel neuro rhythm-aware EEG decoding framework that:\n1. Transforms 1D EEG time series into 2D tensors by modeling dynamic rhythmic properties\n2. Uses NeuroRhythm module to adaptively extract rhythmic structures\n3. Employs 2D convolutional operations to capture temporal dynamics\n4. Disentangles intra-rhythm and inter-rhythm informational structures\n\n## Key Technical Innovation\n**Rhythm-space projection**: \n- Identifies dominant EEG rhythms using FFT\n- Selects top-k frequency bins with largest amplitudes\n- Reshapes temporal sequence into 2D tensors based on rhythm lengths\n- Creates locality for both intra-rhythm (columns) and inter-rhythm (rows) variations\n\n**NeuroRhythmBlock (NRBlock)**:\n- Residual architecture\n- Projects 1D temporal sequence into 2D rhythm-representation space\n- Uses parameter-efficient Inception block for multi-scale 2D kernels\n- Aggregates features from different rhythms weighted by amplitude\n- Shares InceptionBlock across different 2D tensors for efficiency\n\n## Training Pipeline Components\n1. **Preprocessing**: Minimal (temporal cropping, 0.5Hz high-pass filter)\n2. **Normalization**:\n   - Euclidean Alignment (EA) for domain-invariant space\n   - Standardization\n   - Session-wise statistics (not subject-wise)\n   - Personalized Batch Normalization during testing\n3. **Regularization**: Mixup data augmentation\n\n## Evaluation Setup\n**Datasets**:\n- BCI4-2A: 9 subjects, 22 channels, 4 classes, 250Hz, 288 trials/session\n- Zhou: 4 subjects, 14 channels, 3 classes, 250Hz, 450 trials/subject\n- Cho: 52 subjects, 64 channels, 2 classes, 512Hz→256Hz (downsampled), 200 trials/subject\n- Physionet: 109 subjects, 64 channels, 5 classes, 160Hz, 90 trials/subject\n\n**Evaluation Paradigms**:\n- Within-Subject: Train/test on same subject\n- Cross-Subject (LOSO/LMSO): Train on all subjects except one/multiple\n- Cross-Subject Fine-Tuning: Pre-train, then fine-tune on target subject\n\n## Key Results\n\n**Within-Subject (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 79.1% (average)\n- EEGNet: 68.9%\n- EEG-Inception: 73.5%\n- EEG-Conformer: 78.6%\n- LMDA-Net: 78.8%\n- MSVTNet: 78.5%\n\n**Cross-Subject (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 72.1%\n- EEG-ITNet: 69.4%\n- EEG-TCNet: 65.1%\n- EEGNet: 64.0%\n- EEG-Inception: 63.5%\n- MSVTNet: 64.1%\n\n**Cross-Subject with Fine-Tuning (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 85.0% ± 5.9 (Std)\n- EEG-ITNet: 78.7% ± 8.7\n- EEG-TCNet: 76.0% ± 9.9\n- BDAN-SPD: 77.5% ± 15.2\n- EEG-Inception: 75.0% ± 9.4\n- EEGNet: 73.9% ± 10.4\n\n**Cross-Subject (Other Datasets)**:\n- Zhou: 81.1%\n- Cho: 74.9%\n- Physionet: 68.1%\n\n**Ablation Study (Cross-Subject)**:\n- Full pipeline: 72.1% (BCI4-2A)\n- -BN: 65.5% (-4.1 gain)\n- -EA: 67.1% (-2.2 gain)\n- -Session: 70.3% (-3.3 gain)\n- -Mixup: 69.3% (-2.5 gain)\n- -Everything: 58.1% (-7.7 gain)\n\n## Claims Made by Authors\n1. Rhythm-based modeling is effective for MI-BCI decoding\n2. EEGNRNet achieves state-of-the-art performance in cross-subject evaluation\n3. The method shows good stability and generalizability\n4. The training pipeline components (BN, EA, session-wise statistics, Mixup) are effective\n5. 2D representation enables bridging EEG analysis with computer vision backbones\n\n## Known/Potential Weaknesses\n- Limited interpretability of what the 2D rhythm space actually represents\n- Hyperparameter k (number of rhythms) - what''s the optimal value and why?\n- The method adds computational complexity compared to 1D approaches\n- No discussion of failure cases or when rhythm modeling doesn''t help\n- Missing statistical significance tests\n- Limited discussion of biological plausibility of the rhythm-space representation\n\n## Specific Questions for Review\n1. Is the rhythm-space transformation theoretically sound or just an engineering trick?\n2. Are the gains over baselines significant enough to justify the added complexity?\n3. What''s the contribution of the rhythm modeling vs. the training pipeline improvements?\n4. Missing experiments: What happens with different k values? What about ablation of the 2D transformation itself?\n5. Is the claim of "state-of-the-art" justified given the baselines compared?\n6. What''s the narrative arc? Is it compelling for a top venue?\n\nPlease be brutally honest. Identify:\n1. Logical gaps or unjustified claims\n2. Missing experiments that would strengthen the story\n3. Narrative weaknesses\n4. Whether the contribution is sufficient for a top venue like NeurIPS/ICML\n5. Specific recommendations for improvement\n\nFocus on ACTIONABLE feedback - what experiment would fix each concern you identify?','\n',char(10)),'{"type":"managed","file_system":{"type":"restricted","entries":[{"path":{"type":"special","value":{"kind":"root"}},"access":"read"}]},"network":"restricted"}','on-request',131565,1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'0.125.0',replace('I''m going to present a complete ML research paper for your critical review. Please act as a senior ML reviewer (NeurIPS/ICML level) and provide a comprehensive assessment.\n\n## Paper Title\nEEGNRNet: A Neuro Rhythm-aware Network for Motor Imagery Brain–Computer Interface\n\n## Venue\nSubmitted to Neurocomputing (journal)\n\n## Authors\nZhiqiang Li, Guoqiang Hu, Wei Zhao, Junning Deng, Xinqiang Xie\n\n## Problem Statement\nMotor imagery electroencephalogram (MI EEG) decoding is a core challenge in BCI systems. The rhythmic structure of EEG signals exhibits:\n- Multi-frequency coexistence\n- Dynamic temporal variations  \n- Significant inter-subject variability\n\nThese properties challenge conventional decoding methods in terms of robustness and generalizability.\n\n## Proposed Solution: EEGNRNet\nA novel neuro rhythm-aware EEG decoding framework that:\n1. Transforms 1D EEG time series into 2D tensors by modeling dynamic rhythmic properties\n2. Uses NeuroRhythm module to adaptively extract rhythmic structures\n3. Employs 2D convolutional operations to capture temporal dynamics\n4. Disentangles intra-rhythm and inter-rhythm informational structures\n\n## Key Technical Innovation\n**Rhythm-space projection**: \n- Identifies dominant EEG rhythms using FFT\n- Selects top-k frequency bins with largest amplitudes\n- Reshapes temporal sequence into 2D tensors based on rhythm lengths\n- Creates locality for both intra-rhythm (columns) and inter-rhythm (rows) variations\n\n**NeuroRhythmBlock (NRBlock)**:\n- Residual architecture\n- Projects 1D temporal sequence into 2D rhythm-representation space\n- Uses parameter-efficient Inception block for multi-scale 2D kernels\n- Aggregates features from different rhythms weighted by amplitude\n- Shares InceptionBlock across different 2D tensors for efficiency\n\n## Training Pipeline Components\n1. **Preprocessing**: Minimal (temporal cropping, 0.5Hz high-pass filter)\n2. **Normalization**:\n   - Euclidean Alignment (EA) for domain-invariant space\n   - Standardization\n   - Session-wise statistics (not subject-wise)\n   - Personalized Batch Normalization during testing\n3. **Regularization**: Mixup data augmentation\n\n## Evaluation Setup\n**Datasets**:\n- BCI4-2A: 9 subjects, 22 channels, 4 classes, 250Hz, 288 trials/session\n- Zhou: 4 subjects, 14 channels, 3 classes, 250Hz, 450 trials/subject\n- Cho: 52 subjects, 64 channels, 2 classes, 512Hz→256Hz (downsampled), 200 trials/subject\n- Physionet: 109 subjects, 64 channels, 5 classes, 160Hz, 90 trials/subject\n\n**Evaluation Paradigms**:\n- Within-Subject: Train/test on same subject\n- Cross-Subject (LOSO/LMSO): Train on all subjects except one/multiple\n- Cross-Subject Fine-Tuning: Pre-train, then fine-tune on target subject\n\n## Key Results\n\n**Within-Subject (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 79.1% (average)\n- EEGNet: 68.9%\n- EEG-Inception: 73.5%\n- EEG-Conformer: 78.6%\n- LMDA-Net: 78.8%\n- MSVTNet: 78.5%\n\n**Cross-Subject (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 72.1%\n- EEG-ITNet: 69.4%\n- EEG-TCNet: 65.1%\n- EEGNet: 64.0%\n- EEG-Inception: 63.5%\n- MSVTNet: 64.1%\n\n**Cross-Subject with Fine-Tuning (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 85.0% ± 5.9 (Std)\n- EEG-ITNet: 78.7% ± 8.7\n- EEG-TCNet: 76.0% ± 9.9\n- BDAN-SPD: 77.5% ± 15.2\n- EEG-Inception: 75.0% ± 9.4\n- EEGNet: 73.9% ± 10.4\n\n**Cross-Subject (Other Datasets)**:\n- Zhou: 81.1%\n- Cho: 74.9%\n- Physionet: 68.1%\n\n**Ablation Study (Cross-Subject)**:\n- Full pipeline: 72.1% (BCI4-2A)\n- -BN: 65.5% (-4.1 gain)\n- -EA: 67.1% (-2.2 gain)\n- -Session: 70.3% (-3.3 gain)\n- -Mixup: 69.3% (-2.5 gain)\n- -Everything: 58.1% (-7.7 gain)\n\n## Claims Made by Authors\n1. Rhythm-based modeling is effective for MI-BCI decoding\n2. EEGNRNet achieves state-of-the-art performance in cross-subject evaluation\n3. The method shows good stability and generalizability\n4. The training pipeline components (BN, EA, session-wise statistics, Mixup) are effective\n5. 2D representation enables bridging EEG analysis with computer vision backbones\n\n## Known/Potential Weaknesses\n- Limited interpretability of what the 2D rhythm space actually represents\n- Hyperparameter k (number of rhythms) - what''s the optimal value and why?\n- The method adds computational complexity compared to 1D approaches\n- No discussion of failure cases or when rhythm modeling doesn''t help\n- Missing statistical significance tests\n- Limited discussion of biological plausibility of the rhythm-space representation\n\n## Specific Questions for Review\n1. Is the rhythm-space transformation theoretically sound or just an engineering trick?\n2. Are the gains over baselines significant enough to justify the added complexity?\n3. What''s the contribution of the rhythm modeling vs. the training pipeline improvements?\n4. Missing experiments: What happens with different k values? What about ablation of the 2D transformation itself?\n5. Is the claim of "state-of-the-art" justified given the baselines compared?\n6. What''s the narrative arc? Is it compelling for a top venue?\n\nPlease be brutally honest. Identify:\n1. Logical gaps or unjustified claims\n2. Missing experiments that would strengthen the story\n3. Narrative weaknesses\n4. Whether the contribution is sufficient for a top venue like NeurIPS/ICML\n5. Specific recommendations for improvement\n\nFocus on ACTIONABLE feedback - what experiment would fix each concern you identify?','\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,'enabled','gpt-5.5','xhigh',NULL,1777261016837,1779967762967,NULL,replace('I''m going to present a complete ML research paper for your critical review. Please act as a senior ML reviewer (NeurIPS/ICML level) and provide a comprehensive assessment.\n\n## Paper Title\nEEGNRNet: A Neuro Rhythm-aware Network for Motor Imagery Brain–Computer Interface\n\n## Venue\nSubmitted to Neurocomputing (journal)\n\n## Authors\nZhiqiang Li, Guoqiang Hu, Wei Zhao, Junning Deng, Xinqiang Xie\n\n## Problem Statement\nMotor imagery electroencephalogram (MI EEG) decoding is a core challenge in BCI systems. The rhythmic structure of EEG signals exhibits:\n- Multi-frequency coexistence\n- Dynamic temporal variations  \n- Significant inter-subject variability\n\nThese properties challenge conventional decoding methods in terms of robustness and generalizability.\n\n## Proposed Solution: EEGNRNet\nA novel neuro rhythm-aware EEG decoding framework that:\n1. Transforms 1D EEG time series into 2D tensors by modeling dynamic rhythmic properties\n2. Uses NeuroRhythm module to adaptively extract rhythmic structures\n3. Employs 2D convolutional operations to capture temporal dynamics\n4. Disentangles intra-rhythm and inter-rhythm informational structures\n\n## Key Technical Innovation\n**Rhythm-space projection**: \n- Identifies dominant EEG rhythms using FFT\n- Selects top-k frequency bins with largest amplitudes\n- Reshapes temporal sequence into 2D tensors based on rhythm lengths\n- Creates locality for both intra-rhythm (columns) and inter-rhythm (rows) variations\n\n**NeuroRhythmBlock (NRBlock)**:\n- Residual architecture\n- Projects 1D temporal sequence into 2D rhythm-representation space\n- Uses parameter-efficient Inception block for multi-scale 2D kernels\n- Aggregates features from different rhythms weighted by amplitude\n- Shares InceptionBlock across different 2D tensors for efficiency\n\n## Training Pipeline Components\n1. **Preprocessing**: Minimal (temporal cropping, 0.5Hz high-pass filter)\n2. **Normalization**:\n   - Euclidean Alignment (EA) for domain-invariant space\n   - Standardization\n   - Session-wise statistics (not subject-wise)\n   - Personalized Batch Normalization during testing\n3. **Regularization**: Mixup data augmentation\n\n## Evaluation Setup\n**Datasets**:\n- BCI4-2A: 9 subjects, 22 channels, 4 classes, 250Hz, 288 trials/session\n- Zhou: 4 subjects, 14 channels, 3 classes, 250Hz, 450 trials/subject\n- Cho: 52 subjects, 64 channels, 2 classes, 512Hz→256Hz (downsampled), 200 trials/subject\n- Physionet: 109 subjects, 64 channels, 5 classes, 160Hz, 90 trials/subject\n\n**Evaluation Paradigms**:\n- Within-Subject: Train/test on same subject\n- Cross-Subject (LOSO/LMSO): Train on all subjects except one/multiple\n- Cross-Subject Fine-Tuning: Pre-train, then fine-tune on target subject\n\n## Key Results\n\n**Within-Subject (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 79.1% (average)\n- EEGNet: 68.9%\n- EEG-Inception: 73.5%\n- EEG-Conformer: 78.6%\n- LMDA-Net: 78.8%\n- MSVTNet: 78.5%\n\n**Cross-Subject (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 72.1%\n- EEG-ITNet: 69.4%\n- EEG-TCNet: 65.1%\n- EEGNet: 64.0%\n- EEG-Inception: 63.5%\n- MSVTNet: 64.1%\n\n**Cross-Subject with Fine-Tuning (BCI4-2A)**:\n- EEGNRNet: 85.0% ± 5.9 (Std)\n- EEG-ITNet: 78.7% ± 8.7\n- EEG-TCNet: 76.0% ± 9.9\n- BDAN-SPD: 77.5% ± 15.2\n- EEG-Inception: 75.0% ± 9.4\n- EEGNet: 73.9% ± 10.4\n\n**Cross-Subject (Other Datasets)**:\n- Zhou: 81.1%\n- Cho: 74.9%\n- Physionet: 68.1%\n\n**Ablation Study (Cross-Subject)**:\n- Full pipeline: 72.1% (BCI4-2A)\n- -BN: 65.5% (-4.1 gain)\n- -EA: 67.1% (-2.2 gain)\n- -Session: 70.3% (-3.3 gain)\n- -Mixup: 69.3% (-2.5 gain)\n- -Everything: 58.1% (-7.7 gain)\n\n## Claims Made by Authors\n1. Rhythm-based modeling is effective for MI-BCI decoding\n2. EEGNRNet achieves state-of-the-art performance in cross-subject evaluation\n3. The method shows good stability and generalizability\n4. The training pipeline components (BN, EA, session-wise statistics, Mixup) are effective\n5. 2D representation enables bridging EEG analysis with computer vision backbones\n\n## Known/Potential Weaknesses\n- Limited interpretability of what the 2D rhythm space actually represents\n- Hyperparameter k (number of rhythms) - what''s the optimal value and why?\n- The method adds computational complexity compared to 1D approaches\n- No discussion of failure cases or when rhythm modeling doesn''t help\n- Missing statistical significance tests\n- Limited discussion of biological plausibility of the rhythm-space representation\n\n## Specific Questions for Review\n1. Is the rhythm-space transformation theoretically sound or just an engineering trick?\n2. Are the gains over baselines significant enough to justify the added complexity?\n3. What''s the contribution of the rhythm modeling vs. the training pipeline improvements?\n4. Missing experiments: What happens with different k values? What about ablation of the 2D transformation itself?\n5. Is the claim of "state-of-the-art" justified given the baselines compared?\n6. What''s the narrative arc? Is it compelling for a top venue?\n\nPlease be brutally honest. Identify:\n1. Logical gaps or unjustified claims\n2. Missing experiments that would strengthen the story\n3. Narrative weaknesses\n4. Whether the contribution is sufficient for a top venue like NeurIPS/ICML\n5. Specific recommendations for improvement\n\nFocus on ACTIONABLE feedback - what experiment would fix each concern you identify?','\n',char(10)),1779967762,1779967762967,'legacy');
