d PR, issue, and review-adjacent data without depending on a local checkout. If the repository is not already identifiable from the user request or local git context, ask for the repo instead of pretendin<truncated omitted_approx_tokens="120" />e PRs, issues, patches, comments, labels, reactions, or repository state\015\012   - `review follow-up`: unresolved review threads, requested changes, or inline review feedback\015\012   - `CI debugging`: failing checks, Actions logs, or CI root-cause analysis\015\012   - `publish changes`: create or switch branches, stage changes, commit, push, and open a draft PR\015\0123. Route to the specialist skill as soon as the category is clear:\015\012   - Review comments and requested changes: `../gh-address-comments/SKILL.md`\015\012   - Failing GitHub Actions checks: `../gh-fix-ci/SKILL.md`\015\012   - Commit, push, and open PR: `../yeet/SKILL.md`\015\0124. Keep the hybrid model consistent after routing:\015\012   - connector first for PR and issue data\015\012   - local `git` and `gh` only for the specific gaps the connector does not cover\015\012\015\012## Default Workflow\015\012\015\0121. Resolve repository and item scope.\015\0122. Gather structured PR or issue context through the GitHub app from this plugin.\015\0123. Decide whether the task stays in connector-backed triage or needs a specialist skill.\015\0124. Route immediately when the work becomes review follow-up, CI debugging, or publish workflow.\015\0125. End with a clear summary of what was inspected, what changed, and what remains.\015\012\015\012## Output Expectations\015\012\015\012- For triage requests, return a concise summary of the repository, PR, or issue state and the next likely action.\015\012- For mixed requests, tell the user which specialist path you are taking and why.\015\012- For connector-backed write actions, restate the exact PR, issue, label, or reaction target before applying the change.\015\012- Never imply that GitHub Actions logs are available through the connector alone. That remains a `gh` workflow.\015\012\015\012## Examples\015\012\015\012- "Use GitHub to summarize the open PRs in this repo and tell me what needs attention."\015\012- "Help with this PR."\015\012- "Review the latest comments on PR 482 and tell me what is actionable."\015\012- "Debug the failing checks on this branch."\015\012- "Commit these changes, push them, and open a draft PR."\015\012\015\012\012\012[5] tool exec call: const hits = ALL_TOOLS.filter(x => /github|repo|search/i.test(x.name+" "+x.description)); text(hits)\012\012\012[6] tool exec result: Script completed\012Wall time 0.0 seconds\012Output:\012\012[{"name":"codex_app__create_thread","description":"Tools provided by the Codex app.\n\nCreate a separate Codex thread only when the user explicitly asks for a new or background thread. Use list_projects first, then pass its projectId for repo-scoped work in any local or remote project. Use projectless targets for general tasks. Project targets must choose a local or worktree environment.\n\nexec tool declaration:\n```ts\ndeclare const tools: { codex_app__create_thread(args: {\n  // Do not specify a model unless the user explicitly requests a specific model. Otherwise omit this field so the new thread uses the user''s configured default model. Models and supported reasoning efforts on the calling host: gpt-5.6-sol (Latest frontier agentic coding model.; supported reasoning efforts: low, medium, high, xhigh, max, ultra), gpt-5.6-terra (Balanced agentic coding model for everyday work.; supported reasoning efforts: low, medium, high, xhigh, max, ultra), gpt-5.6-luna (Fast and affordable agentic coding model.; supported reasoning efforts: low, medium, high, xhigh, max), gpt-5.5 (Frontier model for complex coding, research, and real-world work.; supported reasoning efforts: low, medium, high, xhigh), gpt-5.4 (Strong model for everyday coding.; supported reasoning efforts: low, medium, high, xhigh), gpt-5.4-mini (Small, fast, an